:R-HSA-9851151  a           obo:GO_0008150 , owl:NamedIndividual ;
        rdfs:comment        "The cytokines pleiotrophin (PTN) and midikine (MDK) were initially proposed to act as ligands for ALK (Stoica et al, 2001; Stoica et al, 2002; reviewed in Wellstein et al, 2012; Winkler et al, 2014; Herradon and Perez-Garcia, 2014). Binding of PTN or MDK to ALK either in cell-free assays or in intact cells was shown to stimulate signaling through IRS, SHC, PLC and PI3K and to support neurite outgrowth, growth and survival (Stoica et al, 2001; Stoica et al, 2002; reviewed in Wellstein et al, 2012; Winkler et al, 2014; Herradon and Perez-Garcia, 2014). The activating effects of PTN and MDK on the ALK receptor were not universally reproducible, however, despite eliciting similar downstream signaling to those with anti-ALK monoclonal antibodies (Mathivet et al, 2007; Moog-Lutz et al, 2005; Motegi et al, 2004; Dirks et al, 2002; Miyake et al, 2002). More recently, ALKAL1 and ALKAL2 have been identified as the physiologically relevant ALK ligands (Zhang et al, 2014; Guan et al, 2015; Reshetnyak et al, 2015; Reshetnyak et al, 2018)." ;
        rdfs:label          "MDK and PTN in ALK signaling" ;
        dc:contributor      "GOC:reactome_curators" , "Reviewed: Turner, Suzanne, 2023-11-08" , "Edited: Rothfels, Karen, 2023-10-14" , "Authored: Rothfels, Karen, 2023-10-14" ;
        dc:date             "2026-06-29" ;
        pav:providedBy      "https://reactome.org" ;
        oboInOwl:hasDbXref  "R-HSA-9851151" ;
        skos:narrower       <http://model.geneontology.org/R-HSA-201556/R-HSA-201556> ;
        skos:note           "org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.Pathway" .

